5
00:00:17,190 --> 00:00:22,440
What retail traders do is overcomplicate their
candlestick trading and focus on things that

6
00:00:22,440 --> 00:00:23,460
are not necessary.

7
00:00:23,460 --> 00:00:29,230
For example, they start memorizing 40 or 50
types of candlestick formations and when they

8
00:00:29,230 --> 00:00:34,730
start analyzing a market, they have to consider
50 variables before making a decision.

9
00:00:34,730 --> 00:00:38,199
I’ve made the same mistake when I first
started trading.

10
00:00:38,199 --> 00:00:42,839
You know what happens when you overcomplicate
your analysis: you start missing out on good

11
00:00:42,839 --> 00:00:48,109
trade setups, you are letting your losing
positions run, and in general you are overthinking

12
00:00:48,109 --> 00:00:49,149
all the time.

13
00:00:49,149 --> 00:00:52,019
So let’s simply candlestick trading.

14
00:00:52,019 --> 00:00:58,789
Among the dozens of candlestick formations,
there are six basic candlesticks types.

15
00:00:58,789 --> 00:01:00,049
1.

16
00:01:00,049 --> 00:01:01,279
Long candlesticks.

17
00:01:01,279 --> 00:01:07,320
The long candlestick indicates a lot of momentum
among buyers or sellers.

18
00:01:07,320 --> 00:01:11,939
The lack of shadow indicates exceptional strength
for one side or the other.

19
00:01:11,939 --> 00:01:16,950
A long candlestick may have no shadows, or
a small one at the top or at the bottom of

20
00:01:16,950 --> 00:01:18,170
the real body.

21
00:01:18,170 --> 00:01:23,189
The significance of the long candlestick relies
completely on its location.

22
00:01:23,189 --> 00:01:28,750
For example, a long green candlestick appearing
within an uptrend could be a strong confirmation

23
00:01:28,750 --> 00:01:33,640
signal, but if the same candlestick appears
after a downtrend, it is more likely to act

24
00:01:33,640 --> 00:01:36,380
as a potential reversal signal.

25
00:01:36,380 --> 00:01:39,399
The same is true for long red candlesticks.

26
00:01:39,399 --> 00:01:44,590
Within a downtrend, it tends to confirm it,
and when it follows an uptrend, it is more

27
00:01:44,590 --> 00:01:47,540
likely to signal a reversal.

28
00:01:47,540 --> 00:01:49,049
2.

29
00:01:49,049 --> 00:01:52,079
Short candlesticks.

30
00:01:52,079 --> 00:01:57,549
A candlestick with average or relatively small
range signals a general agreement between

31
00:01:57,549 --> 00:02:02,869
buyers and sellers that the current price
is reasonable, especially when short candlesticks

32
00:02:02,869 --> 00:02:06,460
appear in a series of sideways-moving sessions.

33
00:02:06,460 --> 00:02:12,849
However, when short candlesticks appear following
a period of strong trend in either direction,

34
00:02:12,849 --> 00:02:17,909
especially when long candlesticks have shown
up, they can indicate a struggle between buyers

35
00:02:17,909 --> 00:02:24,060
and sellers and a likely reversal in the trend,
or a slowing down in price momentum.

36
00:02:24,060 --> 00:02:28,569
The appearance of a single short candlestick
is not meaningful by itself.

37
00:02:28,569 --> 00:02:33,540
When a series of short candlesticks appear,
it may show declining momentum in the current

38
00:02:33,540 --> 00:02:37,400
trend or be a symptom of sideways movement.

39
00:02:37,400 --> 00:02:39,000
3.

40
00:02:39,000 --> 00:02:42,210
Doji candles.

41
00:02:42,210 --> 00:02:48,489
The candle with no real body, or a very narrow-range
—one in which open and close are the same—represents

42
00:02:48,489 --> 00:02:50,810
a significant development.

43
00:02:50,810 --> 00:02:56,239
The fact that price opens and closes at the
same place has greater significance when the

44
00:02:56,239 --> 00:03:01,970
doji also has exceptionally long upper or
lower shadows, or both.

45
00:03:01,970 --> 00:03:08,860
The longer shadows reveal an attempt by buyers
or sellers to move price in the desired direction.

46
00:03:08,860 --> 00:03:15,360
However, the effort failed when price retreat
to close at the same price as the open.

47
00:03:15,360 --> 00:03:20,720
The meaning of the failure on one side or
the other, or on both sides, affects how the

48
00:03:20,720 --> 00:03:26,080
current trend is viewed and what it means
in terms of likely reversal.

49
00:03:26,080 --> 00:03:31,879
For example, when a doji appears at the bottom
of a downtrend and also has an exceptionally

50
00:03:31,879 --> 00:03:38,640
long lower shadow, it shows that sellers tried
to move price lower but couldn’t; this hints

51
00:03:38,640 --> 00:03:42,739
at a likely reversal and a possible movement
to the upside.

52
00:03:42,739 --> 00:03:48,409
If a doji appears at the top of an uptrend
and also has a very long upper shadow, the

53
00:03:48,409 --> 00:03:52,659
same failed attempt is shown, this time among
buyers.

54
00:03:52,659 --> 00:03:56,840
This foreshadows a likely reversal and a possible
down movement.

55
00:03:56,840 --> 00:04:02,580
However, just as long candlesticks indicate
exceptional strength, doji candles indicate

56
00:04:02,580 --> 00:04:09,860
a loss of momentum and, based on the appearance
of any shadows, provide strong reversal signals.

57
00:04:09,860 --> 00:04:13,219
Confirmation is essential to these interpretations,
but we’ll talk about confirmation later

58
00:04:13,219 --> 00:04:16,640
in the video.

59
00:04:16,640 --> 00:04:19,730
4.

60
00:04:19,730 --> 00:04:22,040
Long upper and lower shadows
One of the most interesting signals is an

61
00:04:22,040 --> 00:04:26,610
exceptionally long shadow appearing on both
sides of the real body.

62
00:04:26,610 --> 00:04:32,330
When such shadows are found in both upper
and lower ends in comparison to the real body,

63
00:04:32,330 --> 00:04:38,000
it shows that neither buyers nor sellers had
enough power to move price beyond the opening

64
00:04:38,000 --> 00:04:39,700
and closing range.

65
00:04:39,700 --> 00:04:45,880
This failure of both sides to control price
movement could be a sign of a period of consolidation.

66
00:04:45,880 --> 00:04:51,330
When a candlestick is up with long shadows
on both sides and a current trend has been

67
00:04:51,330 --> 00:04:56,600
underway, it can signal the end of that trend,
even though both sides were unable to create

68
00:04:56,600 --> 00:04:57,980
more movement.

69
00:04:57,980 --> 00:05:03,890
In general, long shadows both above and below
the real body may be better understood in

70
00:05:03,890 --> 00:05:06,070
a multiple time frame analysis.

71
00:05:06,070 --> 00:05:07,150
5.

72
00:05:07,150 --> 00:05:14,040
Long upper shadow only
When a candle contains an unusually long upper

73
00:05:14,040 --> 00:05:20,500
shadow, it signals that buyers have lost momentum
or failed in an effort to take momentum away

74
00:05:20,500 --> 00:05:21,660
from sellers.

75
00:05:21,660 --> 00:05:27,660
If this pattern unfolds at the top of an uptrend,
it is a signal that the trend may be about

76
00:05:27,660 --> 00:05:28,780
to end.

77
00:05:28,780 --> 00:05:34,460
If it shows up within a downtrend, it may
confirm or establish continuation; buyers

78
00:05:34,460 --> 00:05:37,190
tried to reverse the downtrend, but failed.

79
00:05:37,190 --> 00:05:43,030
A long upper shadow candle often appears at
the top of an up move and is often the lowest

80
00:05:43,030 --> 00:05:46,970
point in the downtrend and signals a reversal
point.

81
00:05:46,970 --> 00:05:48,020
6.

82
00:05:48,020 --> 00:05:52,220
Long lower shadow only.

83
00:05:52,220 --> 00:05:57,380
The appearance of a candlestick with a long
lower shadow indicates a failure by sellers

84
00:05:57,380 --> 00:06:01,970
to move price lower, which leads to the immediate
conclusion that either the current downtrend

85
00:06:01,970 --> 00:06:05,600
is ending, or an existing uptrend is continuing.

86
00:06:05,600 --> 00:06:10,440
However, the pattern can have either a bullish
or a bearish interpretation.

87
00:06:10,440 --> 00:06:15,280
The interesting thing about this pattern is
that it can be bullish or bearish, depending

88
00:06:15,280 --> 00:06:17,150
on where it appears.

89
00:06:17,150 --> 00:06:22,080
The real body may also be either green or
red, without affecting the interpretation

90
00:06:22,080 --> 00:06:23,460
of the candle.

91
00:06:23,460 --> 00:06:28,520
A long lower shadow candle often appears at
the bottom of a down move and is often the

92
00:06:28,520 --> 00:06:34,750
highest point in the uptrend and signals the
reversal point.

93
00:06:34,750 --> 00:06:37,840
Confirmation

94
00:06:37,840 --> 00:06:40,630
So now you have 6 candlestick types to analyze.

95
00:06:40,630 --> 00:06:47,970
But with all forms of candlesticks, “significance”
is a matter of market context, or market structure.

96
00:06:47,970 --> 00:06:52,710
Also, candlestick patterns do not always have
to mean anything of interest.

97
00:06:52,710 --> 00:06:58,520
Some signals are really not signals at all;
this is why confirmation is so important.

98
00:06:58,520 --> 00:07:00,990
Confirmation is an important aspect of candlestick
analysis.

99
00:07:00,990 --> 00:07:07,260
It is the observation of separate and independent
signals that verify what the candlestick pattern

100
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:08,450
predicts.

101
00:07:08,450 --> 00:07:14,830
For example, a candlestick reversal may be
confirmed by tests of resistance or support,

102
00:07:14,830 --> 00:07:19,230
momentum changes, or even by moving average-based
analysis.

103
00:07:19,230 --> 00:07:25,480
Two or more candlestick signals may occur
in proximity, providing very strong confirmation.

104
00:07:25,480 --> 00:07:30,580
A test of resistance or support, for example,
may be first made by a familiar technical

105
00:07:30,580 --> 00:07:36,640
signal (such as double top or double bottom)
and then confirmed by strong reversal candlestick

106
00:07:36,640 --> 00:07:38,080
signals.

107
00:07:38,080 --> 00:07:43,700
Or a candlestick reversal may first appear
and then be confirmed by failed tests of resistance

108
00:07:43,700 --> 00:07:45,930
or support.

109
00:07:45,930 --> 00:07:50,640
You need to rely on confirmation to improve
your timing of entry and exit.

110
00:07:50,640 --> 00:07:55,860
The concept is necessary because no single
candlestick pattern is always reliable.

111
00:07:55,860 --> 00:08:01,250
Even confirmed signals may fail; however,
with the use of confirmation, the ratio of

112
00:08:01,250 --> 00:08:06,900
successful trade timing improves and failed
signals are more easily spotted when a secondary

113
00:08:06,900 --> 00:08:12,610
indicator contradicts rather than confirms
what the initial signal indicates.

114
00:08:12,610 --> 00:08:17,390
A confirming indicator may also consist of
a second sign of the same type.

115
00:08:17,390 --> 00:08:23,460
For example, an initial candlestick reversal
may be followed by an equally strong but different

116
00:08:23,460 --> 00:08:26,620
candlestick revealing the same potential.

117
00:08:26,620 --> 00:08:32,430
When this occurs, the reliability of the dual
signal is much stronger.

118
00:08:32,430 --> 00:08:36,959
So the initial goal of confirmation is to
improve timing for trades.

119
00:08:36,959 --> 00:08:42,430
Another value is found in how a confirming
indicator identifies and confirms a bigger

120
00:08:42,430 --> 00:08:43,430
trend.

121
00:08:43,430 --> 00:08:48,730
A price trend may last only a few sessions,
or extend for weeks or even months.

122
00:08:48,730 --> 00:08:55,209
In my own trading, I rely on confirmation
from moving averages, volume trends, and divergences.

123
00:08:55,209 --> 00:09:00,180
These are valuable in identifying the likelihood
of a trend continuing or ending.

124
00:09:00,180 --> 00:09:05,800
In this respect, confirmation not only affects
the turning point in price, but it also can

125
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:11,360
anticipate an overall weakening in momentum
or development of a period of consolidation

126
00:09:11,360 --> 00:09:16,540
after a strong or rapid trend has run its
course.

127
00:09:16,540 --> 00:09:21,180
Confirmation is also valuable when used to
time entry and exit within the context of

128
00:09:21,180 --> 00:09:24,199
existing resistance and support levels.

129
00:09:24,199 --> 00:09:29,490
For example, there’s a tendency for price
to remain within the trading range until a

130
00:09:29,490 --> 00:09:32,110
signal changes current conditions.

131
00:09:32,110 --> 00:09:37,310
So a failed attempt to break out of the trading
range is likely to lead to a price movement

132
00:09:37,310 --> 00:09:39,110
in the opposite direction.

133
00:09:39,110 --> 00:09:44,670
When this occurs and separate confirmation
is found in candlestick formations, the reversal

134
00:09:44,670 --> 00:09:48,290
has a better than average likelihood of taking
place.

135
00:09:48,290 --> 00:09:53,420
If price does break through resistance or
support, you face an immediate decision point.

136
00:09:53,420 --> 00:09:57,720
Will the trend continue and establish a new
trading range?

137
00:09:57,720 --> 00:10:03,180
Or will the breakout fail and price will return
to previously set levels?

138
00:10:03,180 --> 00:10:08,760
The uncertainty of the outcome of a breakout
can be clarified with confirmation, through

139
00:10:08,760 --> 00:10:12,880
candlestick formations that follow the breakout
itself.

140
00:10:12,880 --> 00:10:17,910
The short-term changes in price direction
and strength may further be confirmed and

141
00:10:17,910 --> 00:10:22,509
tracked with the use of trend lines and other
visual tools.

142
00:10:22,509 --> 00:10:28,029
Following a trend line helps identify when
a short-term trend is likely to reverse, and

143
00:10:28,029 --> 00:10:34,050
if confirmed with candlestick reversal signals,
is a reliable method for tracking and confirming

144
00:10:34,050 --> 00:10:35,759
price and momentum.

145
00:10:35,759 --> 00:10:41,499
An uptrend is marked with a trend line drawn
under the price levels from a low point, and

146
00:10:41,499 --> 00:10:47,230
it continues until it runs into price that
has reached a high and reversed.

147
00:10:47,230 --> 00:10:52,379
A downtrend is marked with a trend line drawn
above the price levels starting from a high

148
00:10:52,379 --> 00:10:58,960
point and continuing downward until price
reaches its low and then turns.

149
00:10:58,960 --> 00:11:03,579
Confirmation comes in many forms and is applied
to short-term or intermediate trends, trading

150
00:11:03,579 --> 00:11:11,050
ranges, and momentum.

151
00:11:11,050 --> 00:11:16,139
Just as important as having confirmation is
the opposite theory of contradiction.

152
00:11:16,139 --> 00:11:20,720
When two reliable candlestick signals do not
agree, the significance is uncertain.

153
00:11:20,720 --> 00:11:22,639
You know the situation.

154
00:11:22,639 --> 00:11:27,920
You get a long lower shadow candlestick after
a downtrend, you wait for confirmation, thinking

155
00:11:27,920 --> 00:11:33,880
to go long, and then price forms a long upper
shadow candle, signaling a possible short

156
00:11:33,880 --> 00:11:34,880
position.

157
00:11:34,880 --> 00:11:37,960
2 candlestick formation that contradict.

158
00:11:37,960 --> 00:11:41,450
Most traders would gamble on this scenario,
would pick a side.

159
00:11:41,450 --> 00:11:45,900
In this instance, you have to choose one of
several courses of action:

160
00:11:45,900 --> 00:11:46,900
1.

161
00:11:46,900 --> 00:11:49,620
To seek confirmation from a new set of candlesticks.

162
00:11:49,620 --> 00:11:50,620
2.

163
00:11:50,620 --> 00:11:53,279
Take no action until the market direction
is clarified.

164
00:11:53,279 --> 00:11:54,279
3.

165
00:11:54,279 --> 00:11:57,759
To analyze volume and look for possible divergences
3.

166
00:11:57,759 --> 00:12:01,459
Or to expand the analysis for more time.

